XIII. 1 From what we have said, we may decide the question moved by many writers, whether a war, regarded in reference to those who are the principal movers of it, ean be just on both sides. We must distinguish various acceptations of the word just. A thing is called just from its cause, or from its est'eet. And again, from its cause, either in the special acceptation of justice, or in that general acceptation in which all rectitudo or rightness comes under that name.
